The <body> of a TAN-R-mor
                  file takes the customary optional attributes found in other TAN files (see
                        @in-progress and
                     ). <body> takes any number of <assert>, <report>, <category> (if relying upon
                  structured codes), or <option>s.

chapter.para:
Put your class 1 files in the root of the library directory. Then put your class 2 or
            class 3 files in their own subdirectory, given the name of their TAN type, e.g.,
            TAN-A-div.
